      "SummaryText": "probability of a release that spreads beyond our plant boundary is very small.  \n\nListed below are some examples of the things we do to prevent releases and reduce the impact of releases that do occur: \n\n(a) Plant equipment is designed carefully, to minimize the probability of a major leak or spill.\n\n(b) All unusual operations, and small leaks or spills are investigated to prevent recurrence.\n\n(c) Safety controls such as instrumentation, warning alarms, monitoring equipment, and automatic shutdown systems are installed.\n\n(d)Thorough routine audits of the process are conducted.\n\n(e) Regular equipment inspections and maintenance insure proper operations.\n\n(f) Training and testing of operators and mechanics ensures they follow safe operating procedures.\n\n4. FIVE YEAR ACCIDENT HISTORY\nUnder the RMP, EPA requires owners or operators to report all accidental releases that resulted in death, injuries, or significant property damage on site, or known offsite deaths, injuries, evacuations, sheltering in place, or property or environmental damage.  There have not been any incidents involving exposures to regulated material that met the five-year accident history reporting criteria.\n\n5. EMERGENCY RESPONSE PROGRAM\nCovoro  has developed a comprehensive Emergency Action Plan that helps us protect the health of the public and our employees and prevent harm to the environment.   The plan establishes the emergency response organization, the training and preparation requirements, the equipment and facilities used for response, and procedures utilized during response.\n\nThe overall site Emergency Action Plan begins with a brief description of the purpose and primary objectives for the plan.   This includes: \n\n(a) Prevent injuries - both on and off-plant\n(b) Minimize property damage\n(c) Minimize interruptions to the continuity of operations\n(d) Maintain security of company property\n(e) Ensure that the site and community are prepared to effectively deal with an incident that has the pot"
